summary:
The Security Council:

Adopted Resolution 1401 (2002) on 28 March 2002.

Reaffirming previous resolutions on Afghanistan, particularly 1378 (2001), 1383 (2001), and 1386 (2001), 
and recalling General Assembly resolution 56/220 (2001), 

The Council:

1. Endorses a 12-month United Nations Assistance Mission in Afghanistan (UNAMA) with the mandate and structure outlined in the Secretary-General's report (S/2002/278);
2. Reaffirms support for the Special Representative of the Secretary-General, endorsing his authority over UN activities in Afghanistan;
3. Urges donors to coordinate with the Special Representative, Afghan Interim Administration, and its successors for recovery and reconstruction assistance;
4. Stresses that recovery or reconstruction assistance should be provided through the Afghan Interim Administration and its successors where local authorities maintain a secure environment and respect human rights;
5. Calls on Afghan parties to cooperate with UNAMA and ensure staff security and freedom of movement;
6. Requests the International Security Assistance Force to work in close consultation with the Secretary-General and his Special Representative;
7. Requests the Secretary-General to report to the Council every four months on the implementation of this resolution;
8. Decides to remain actively seized of the matter.
